{"award_age":56.0,"bio_image":null,"category":"Physics","country":"United Kingdom","date_of_birth":"1918-09-27T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1984-10-14T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":[],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Martin_Ryle","mini_bio":"<p><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Knight_Bachelor\" title=\"Knight Bachelor\">Sir<\/a> <b>Martin Ryle<\/b> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fellow_of_the_Royal_Society\" title=\"Fellow of the Royal Society\" class=\"mw-redirect\">FRS<\/a><sup id=\"cite_ref-frs_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Martin_Ryle#cite_note-frs-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> (27 September 1918\u00a0\u2013 14 October 1984) was an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/England\" title=\"England\">English<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Radio_astronomy\" title=\"Radio astronomy\">radio astronomer<\/a> who developed revolutionary <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Radio_telescope\" title=\"Radio telescope\">radio telescope<\/a> systems (see e.g. <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Aperture_synthesis\" title=\"Aperture synthesis\">aperture synthesis<\/a>) and used them for accurate location and imaging of weak radio sources. In 1946 Ryle and Vonberg were the first people to publish <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Astronomical_interferometer\" title=\"Astronomical interferometer\">interferometric<\/a> astronomical measurements at radio wavelengths, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Joseph_Pawsey\" title=\"Joseph Pawsey\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Joseph Pawsey<\/a> from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Sydney\" title=\"University of Sydney\">University of Sydney<\/a> claimed to have actually made interferometric measurements earlier in the same year. With improved equipment, Ryle observed the most distant known galaxies in the universe at that time. He was the first Professor of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cavendish_Astrophysics_Group\" title=\"Cavendish Astrophysics Group\">Radio Astronomy at the University of Cambridge<\/a>, and founding director of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mullard_Radio_Astronomy_Observatory\" title=\"Mullard Radio Astronomy Observatory\">Mullard Radio Astronomy Observatory<\/a>. He was <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Astronomer_Royal\" title=\"Astronomer Royal\">Astronomer Royal<\/a> from 1972 to 1982.<\/p><p>Ryle and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Antony_Hewish\" title=\"Antony Hewish\">Antony Hewish<\/a> shared the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Physics\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Physics<\/a> in 1974, the first Nobel prize awarded in recognition of astronomical research.<\/p>","name":"Martin Ryle","place_of_birth":"Brighton ,  England","place_of_death":"Cambridge ,  England","text":"Martin Ryle , Physics, 1974","year":1974.0}